we have the benefit of hindsight, so it was very unlikely anybody but Hitler and his highest officials knew how much of their strength was tied up in Poland. Should have France exploited the weak defenses they found? yes but they also were not structured for a fast advance.

but also France and Britain were rightfully afraid of the threat posed by the Luftwaffe which was one of the most power airforces to date. They had no way of knowing most Luftwaffe planes were committed in Poland. There could be 1000 waiting in the Ruhr for all they know.

The Soviet invasion precluded the Polish from digging in for a prolonged defense but it didn't matter because the British and French had no interest in relieving the Polish anyway. France literally invaded a little forest in Germanyr and then got nervous and went back to France.
France had suggested they deploy most of their forces along more defensible positions like the Vistula and San rivers but this didn't work with their want to hold onto every inch of soil.

The Polish plan for defense was very poorly planned and implemented. They did not want to willingly forfeit the Polish corridor which is what they thought Germany was invading over. Mobilization was only 60% successful and they were periodically getting encircled and trapped.

The Soviets had attempted to ally with UK and FR against GER but negotiations failed probably for this reason. so they decided to feign friendship to Hitler so they could take eastern Poland as a buffer against the eventual German invasion they expected would happen eventually.

The British and French were still naively hoping they could stop the conflict diplomatically. They did not understand that Hitler's true motives were not just the Polish corridor and Danzig city but 'Liebestraum' which is basically the german colonization of eastern europe.

The Polish had planned to slowly withdraw across the country into the more rugged terrain along the Romanian border and bog the Germans down there until the French and British could relieve them from a push from the west, which, they were clearly not interested in doing.

When the Nazis invaded Poland they had to commit the vast majority of their forces to the invasion and were left dangerously vulnerable in the West. They had (correctly) gambled that the UK and French would be too cautious and not realize how open the road to Berlin was.
